Embayment MANOVA

This is to perform a MANOVA on the cleaned and log transformed data from the output of the embayment analysis. The imported dataset should only contain the columns (Embayment, Type 1, Lm, Lb , C). The last three of which should be normally distributed (after log transform in this case). First we will import the data.

library('readr')
package readr was built under R version 3.4.4
library('dplyr')

Attaching package: dplyr

The following objects are masked from package:stats:

    filter, lag

The following objects are masked from package:base:

    intersect, setdiff, setequal, union

Next we will plot the qqplots to make sure data is normally distributed.

qqnorm(df$Lm)
qqline(df$Lm, col = 'steelblue', lwd=2)

qqnorm(df$Lb)
qqline(df$Lb, col = 'steelblue', lwd=2)

qqnorm(df$C)
qqline(df$C, col = 'steelblue', lwd=2)

Once we have established that the data is roughly normally distributed we can conduct the MANOVA and post hoc tests.

df.maov <- manova(cbind(Lm, Lb) ~ EmbClass, data = df)
summary(df.maov)

Now that we know that they are both significant we can do one-way ANOVAS and post-hoc tests.

Lm.lm <- lm(df$Lm ~ df$EmbClass, data = df)
Lm.aov<- aov(Lm.lm)
summary(Lm.aov)
            Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value  Pr(>F)    
df$EmbClass  7 114.28  16.326   17.55 1.4e-14 ***
Residuals   92  85.61   0.931                    
---
Signif. codes:  0 *** 0.001 ** 0.01 * 0.05 . 0.1   1
8 observations deleted due to missingness
Lm.hsd<- TukeyHSD(Lm.aov)
Lm.hsd
